The GCP-Nvidia Partnership
--------------------------

Then there is the Nvidia announcement, which has three major components:

* First, Google announced A3 virtual machines, built on Nvidia H100 GPUs. I=
f you need Nvidia GPUs, GCP has them.
* Second, GCP will host Nvidia=E2=80=99s DGX Cloud. This is a cloud service=
 managed by Nvidia that runs on the full Nvidia stack, including their own =
CPUs, networking, etc.; CEO Jensen Huang, who was on stage, also said that =
GCP would host the first instances of Nvidia=E2=80=99s next-generation DGX =
supercomputer (the DGX GH200).
* Third, Huang announced that Nvidia was partnering with Google on PaxML, a=
 large language model framework built on top of Jax and OpenXLA.

This last announcement is very interesting. Jax is a framework used for the=
 development of models, while OpenXLA is a compiler for creating models tha=
t can run on a variety of hardware; this illustration from Google=E2=80=99s=
 announcement of OpenXLA is helpful ( https://opensource.googleblog.com/202=
3/03/openxla-is-ready-to-accelerate-and-simplify-ml-development.html ) :

Understanding OpenXLA ( https://opensource.googleblog.com/2023/03/openxla-i=
s-ready-to-accelerate-and-simplify-ml-development.html )

Here=E2=80=99s my read on this partnership: it firmly establishes Nvidia=E2=
=80=99s dominance in training and gives a big boost to its DGX Cloud, even =
as it gives Google priority access to H100s and creates the conditions for =
Google to bring its TPUs to bear on inference.

