I think the fact that Oracle is leading the way here speaks to why cloud se=
rvice providers would want to support Nvidia in this effort. After all, why=
 is anyone choosing Oracle as their cloud service? Now, though, they aren=
=E2=80=99t choosing Oracle: they=E2=80=99re choosing Nvidia, and Oracle is =
along for the ride, more than willing to implement the full Nvidia stack an=
d perhaps, for that reason, be Nvidia=E2=80=99s preferred provider.

DGX Cloud, meanwhile, is targeting Microsoft=E2=80=99s core customer base; =
it makes sense that Microsoft would want to play ball to keep those custome=
rs on Azure, even if it=E2=80=99s lower margin. I=E2=80=99m a little more s=
tumped by Google: I guess they also have an enterprise business to preserve=
, and maybe they are looking for growth wherever they can find it.

Maybe it wasn=E2=80=99t growth GCP was looking for: it very well may have b=
een H100s. Back to Kurian:

Google and Nvidia have had such a long partnership, not only bringing the b=
est Nvidia GPUs to the cloud, but also the software used to develop and dep=
loy AI. Today we use Nvidia GPUs to build our next generation AI and serve =
models for our customers and users. Can you share a little bit about how ou=
r partnership is helping advance the field of AI in a way that benefits all=
 of these customers?

This is when Huang announced the aforementioned PaxML partnership, which ag=
ain, pays off with models that are compiled to run not just run on Nvidia G=
PUs but on accelerators of all kinds, including Google=E2=80=99s TPUs; Huan=
g then announced that GCP would be the launch partner for the aforementione=
d DGX GH200, which again, is part of an Nvidia managed cloud service hosted=
 by GCP.

For us at Google, it=E2=80=99s a natural evolution of the AI market. Many p=
eople ask me what=E2=80=99s the relationship between TPUs, GPUs, how do you=
 think about it. Very simply put, as AI evolves, the needs on the hardware =
architecture and software stack evolves from training to inferencing to new=
 capabilities like embeddings, and we want to offer customer the broadest m=
ost optimized choice of accelerators.

That=E2=80=99s the other thing GCP wants: even if Nvidia wins in training, =
it wants to leverage its TPU advantage for inference. Huang, meanwhile, eff=
ectively makes GCP the flagship partner for DGX, a significant step-up from=
 Oracle.

We=E2=80=99re also a platforms company. Google is a platforms company at th=
e heart of it, and we want to attract all those developers and customers wh=
o love Nvidia=E2=80=99s GPU technology, your software, so it=E2=80=99s a gr=
eat partnership.

Kurian probably should have stuck with =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99re=E2=80=9D; Goo=
gle does not have the best reputation as a reliable platform company! It is=
 admirable, though, the extent to which Kurian has worked to establish GCP =
specifically as something customers can rely on. Go back to the first annou=
ncement I mentioned above, about supporting Llama 2 and Code Llama: that=E2=
=80=99s the move of a platform company willing to give customers what they =
want, not simply throw internally-developed technology over the fence, and =
it=E2=80=99s not a surprise that GCP=E2=80=99s press push led with it.

What customers want most of all, though, is access to Nvidia=E2=80=99s GPUs=
, which means GCP wants Nvidia GPUs, both for itself and Google proper, alo=
ng with increased software support for running inference for models trained=
 on Nvidia GPUs on their own TPUs; if that means becoming what is basically=
 an OEM for Nvidia=E2=80=99s own self-branded cloud, so be it.

